text: SYNLETT0936-52141437-2096 © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York 2020, 31, A–F letter en Synthetic Study on Lactonamycins, Part 2: Stereoselective Access  to ABCD-Ring System Hiroshi Takikawa1   Kazuki Murata  Keisuke Suzuki* 0000-0001-7935-3762 Department of Chemistry, Tokyo Institute of Technology,  2-12-1 O-okayama, Meguro-ku, Tokyo 152-8551, Japan ksuzuki@chem.titech.ac.jp Dedicated to the memory of Prof. Hidetoshi Yamada Lactonamycin  (1a;  Figure  1)  is  an  antitumor  antibiotic with  bactericidal  activity  against  drug-resistant  patho- gens.2  Congener  1b  with  a  different  sugar  has  also  been identified.3 They share a common heterocyclic aglycon that includes two oxacycles (the A and B rings) and a -lactam (the F ring). A structural signature of the lactonamycins is the ABC-ring system, which is a densely functionalized an- gular tricycle with three contiguous quaternary stereogenic centers. The important bioactivities and unique structures of  lactonamycins  have  attracted  considerable  attention,4 leading  to  a  racemic  synthesis  of  the  aglycon  1c  by  the Danishefsky group5 and pioneering total syntheses of 1a by Tatsuta  et  al.6  and  1a  and  1b  by  Nakata  and  Saikawa  and their co-workers.7 In all cases, however, the aglycon 1c was prepared as a racemate and resolved at the glycoside stage. As  part  of  our  ongoing  synthetic  study  on  type-II polyketide polycyclic compounds,8 we became interested in these compounds with particular attention to the possibili- ty of a hitherto unachieved asymmetric synthesis.

As a clue to the enantioselective synthesis, we focused our attention on the cis-diol motif at the BC-ring junction in Received: 28.05.2020 Accepted after revision: 18.06.2020 Published online: 21.07.2020 DOI: 10.1055/s-0040-1707198; Art ID: st-2020-u0318-l Abstract  Toward  a  stereoselective  total  synthesis  of  the  lactonamy- cins, we recently reported an approach to the DEF-ring system. Here we report a model study for constructing the ABCD-ring system, revealing a viable approach through (1) construction of the C-ring by asymmetric benzoin  cyclization,  (2)  introduction  of  an  angular  hydroxy  group through oxidation of an isoxazolium salt, and (3) construction of the AB rings through a ring-opening/closing sequence. Key words  natural products, total synthesis, lactonamycins, aromatic polyketides, isoxazoles, benzoin cyclization © 2020. Thieme. All rights reserved. Synlett 2020, 31, A–F Georg Thieme Verlag KG, Rüdigerstraße 14, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany 1c, associating it with tetracenomycin C (2)8e and pleospdi- one  (3),8d  which  we  recently  synthesized  by  exploiting  a three-step  approach  that  we  had  previously  developed (Scheme 1). Step 1 is the preparation of the isoxazole plat- form9 C by cycloaddition of benzonitrile oxide A and cyclic enone B followed by dehydrogenation.10 Step 2 is an enantio- selective benzoin cyclization of ketoaldehyde C catalyzed by an N-heterocyclic carbene to give tetracycle D with an an- gular hydroxy group.11 Step 3 is two-step hydroxylation via the  corresponding  isoxazolium  salt  to  give  tricycle  E  with an angular cis-diol.12

Biogenetically, the characteristic angular cis-diol struc- tures in 2 and 3 originate from oxidative dearomatizations downstream  of  the  type-II  polyketide  pathway,13  whereas the AB-ring moiety in 1c is derived from an extensive oxi- dative modification of the decaketide-derived tetracycle I, including ring fission (Figure 2).14 1c: R = H   lactonamycinone . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C s t t e s u h c a s s a M In  our  synthetic  study  of  1c,  we  first  studied  the  con- struction  of  the  left  hemisphere,  i.e.,  the  DEF  rings,  which we achieved through the [4+2]-cycloaddition of the alkoxy- furan F and the -alkoxybenzyne G (Scheme 2a).15 Turning our attention to the right hemisphere of 1c with the challenging structure described above, we set tetracycle 4  as  a  model  target  corresponding  to  the  ABCD  rings.  The bottom line was to exploit our three-step approach, aiming at a coherent solution to the following three challenges: (1) enantioselection, (2) diastereoselection (cis-diol), and (3) effective construction of the AB rings. Although the three-step approach gave simple solutions to the syntheses of 2 and 3, its applicability to 3 was not ob- vious,  and  we  reasoned  that  the  key  was  to  design  a  syn- thetic equivalent of the intricate AB-ring system. Here, we describe our model study of the construction of the ABCD- ring system in a stereocontrolled manner.

Scheme 2b shows our retrosynthetic analysis of 4. Dis- connection of the AB rings suggested the -keto ester 5, and connection of the C5-alcohol and the C2-carbonyl (natural- product  numbering)  suggested  the  seven-membered  lac- tone  6.  If  we  assume  that  the  three-step  conversion  dis- cussed above is viable, the 2-hydroxy-1,3-diketone moiety in 6 (red) can be traced back to the isoxazole 7, in which the Scheme 1   Three-step approach Figure 2   Biosynthetic origin of the AB-ring system of the lactonamycins enantioselective benzoin cyclization © 2020. Thieme. All rights reserved. Synlett 2020, 31, A–F lactone in 6 is replaced by the corresponding cyclic ether. Our earlier study suggested that a cyclic structure is a pre- requisite for successful hydroxylation.16 Disconnections by assuming a 1,3-dipolar cycloaddition and a benzoin-form- ing reaction suggested nitrile oxide 817 and cyclic enone 918 as starting materials. The benzoin-forming reaction should provide an opportunity for developing an asymmetric syn- thetic  route.11c,d  As  suggested  by  this  analysis,  the  seven- membered  cyclic  enone  9  indeed  served  as  a  synthetic equivalent of the AB rings, as described below.

Our study began with the regioselective 1,3-dipolar cyc- loaddition of benzonitrile oxide 8 with enone 9 (PhCl, 60 °C, 36  h)  (Scheme  3).19  Subsequent  dehydrogenation  (NiO2, CH2Cl2,  0  °C,  2  h)  followed  by  acid  hydrolysis  (1  M  H2SO4, THF, 0 °C, 2 h) gave keto aldehyde 10 as the sole product, ready for a potential benzoin cyclization. Upon treatment of 10 with the achiral triazolium salt 11a (15 mol%) and Et3N (30 mol%) in THF (rt, 3 h), the reaction proceeded smoothly to give -ketol 12 in 91% yield. . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C s t t e s u h c a s s a M For proof of concept of the opportunity for asymmetric synthesis, keto aldehyde 10 was subjected to an enantiose- lective  benzoin  cyclization.  The  modified  Rovis  chiral  tri- azolium salt 11b (10 mol%)8b,11d,20 worked nicely (THF, rt, 3 h), giving -ketol 12 in 90% yield and with high enantiose- lectivity (93% ee).21

Having proven the viability of the enantioselection, we proceeded to focus on the key hydroxylation stage, and we converted the racemic -ketol 12 into the isoxazolium salt 14 in three steps: stereoselective reduction of the carbonyl group  (NaBH4,  MeOH,  0  °C,  15  min),  dibenzylation  (BnBr, NaH,  1:1  THF–DMF,  0  °C,  4  h),22  and  N-methylation –, MS 4Å, CH2Cl2, rt, 10 h). Pleasingly, upon treat- (Me3O+BF4 ment of 14 with aqueous NaOCl under carefully optimized conditions (pH 8.9, MeCN, –30 °C to rt, 25 min),8a,12 stereo- selective hydroxylation proceeded smoothly to give the de- sired alcohol 15 as a single diastereomer (confirmed by 1H NMR analysis).23 Having  the  key  tricycle  15  in  hand,  we  focused  on  its conversion into the acyclic carboxylic acid H or its equiva- lent by opening of the seven-membered oxacycle, for which we needed to raise the oxidation level at C2 (Scheme 4). Our original  plan  was  to  exploit  a  Saegusa–Ito  oxidation,24  for which we tried to prepare the enol silyl ether by treating 15 with Et3SiOTf and Et3N (CH2Cl2, 0 °C, 10 min); however, this unexpectedly gave the enoate 16 in 90% yield. Formation of this unusual product 16 can be rationalized in terms of the activation of the carbonyl group by Et3SiOTf, and the partic- ipation of the proximal alcohol to form the epoxy silyl ether Scheme 3   Assembly and stereoselection 11a (15 mol%) or 11b (10 mol%) 91% with 11a 90% (93% ee) with 11b

Whereas  protection  by  THP,  MOM,  or  Bn groups failed, acyl groups such as acetyl and benzoyl could be  introduced,  and  finally  a  p-nitrobenzoyl  group  (p- O2NC6H4COCl,  DMAP,  CH2Cl2,  rt,  1  h)  turned  out  to  be  the best choice. Although several hidden pitfalls forced us into tortuous  strategic  changes,  we  eventually  found  a  way  to convert  the  seven-membered  ring  in  the  p-nitrobenzoate 17 into the required AB-ring system. The first strategic change was to give up the projected Saegusa–Ito approach because of the following unexpected result. Treatment of 17 with Me3SiOTf and Et3N (CH2Cl2, rt, 20 h) gave none of the expected enol silyl ether, but instead gave acyclic enone 18 in 61% yield through an eliminative ring opening and an O-silylation.26,27 With this observation, we came up with the idea of an alternative approach using a Pummerer rearrangement in oxidizing the C2 position, for which a conjugate addition of thiophenol to enone 18 was carried out (Et3N, THF, rt, 20 min), giving the desired sulfide 19 in 83% yield.28

For the construction of the B ring, we were examining the detachment of the TMS protecting group from the C5- alcohol  in  19  when  we  met  with  a  second  unexpected event.  Upon  treatment  of  sulfide  19  with  HF·pyridine  in pyridine (0 °C, 10 min), TLC monitoring suggested that the starting material was rapidly consumed to give a new spot, which  we  assumed  to  be  the  liberated  alcohol.  During quenching, extraction, and concentration, however, this TLC spot was converted into another spot that turned out to be cyclic enol ether 20.29 The latter conversion is rationalized by the following sequence of events: (1) the formation of a prim-alcohol,  (2)  conversion  to  a  hemiacetal  (not  shown), (3) an acyl migration to give hemiacylal K, and (4) the elim- Scheme 4   Attempted Saegusa–Ito route . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C s t t e s u h c a s s a M ination of a p-nitrobenzoic acid.30 This was a pleasant sur- prise,  as  the  B-ring  has  been  formed  in  20,  ready  for  the Pummerer reaction. Unfortunately, however, sulfoxide 21, obtained by oxi- dation of sulfide 20 with mCPBA (NaHCO3, CH2Cl2, –60 °C, 30 min), proved to be extremely unstable, and all attempts at  its  Pummerer  rearrangement  failed  to  give  the  desired enal 22. Considering that the decomposition might be facil- Scheme 5   Pummerer route to the AB rings Scheme 6   Pummerer route to the AB rings (continued) 1) NaClO2, NaH2PO4     2-methylbut-2-ene

After  protection  of  20  by  a  Boc  group  [(Boc)2O,  DMAP, CH2Cl2,  0  °C,  10  min]  to  give  23,31  treatment  with  mCPBA (NaHCO3, CH2Cl2, –78 °C, 10 min) gave 71% yield of sulfox- ide 24 (dr = 1.2:1), which was stable enough to allow purifi- cation  by  silica-gel  column  chromatography  (Scheme  6). Upon treatment of sulfoxide 24 with trifluoroacetic anhy- dride (TFAA) and 2,6-lutidine (CH2Cl2, –20 °C, 90 min), the reaction proceeded smoothly to give enal 25 in 43% yield. Dithioacetal 26, obtained in 32% yield as a byproduct,32 was also converted into enal 25 in 70% yield by an oxidative hy- drolysis with PhI(OCOCF3)2 (1:1 MeCN–H2O, 0 °C, 40 min).33 More conveniently, after the Pummerer reaction (–20 °C, 1 h), PhI(OCOCF3)2 and water (rt, 20 min) were added to the reaction  mixture  to  give  25  in  75%  yield  as  the  sole  prod- uct.34 Oxidation of enal 25 to the corresponding carboxylic acid  (NaClO2,  NaH2PO4,  2-methylbut-2-ene,  1:1  t-BuOH– CH2Cl2, rt, 1 h) followed by treatment with TMSCHN2 (1:1 MeOH–CH2Cl2, rt, 10 min) gave ester 27.34

The final step was the construction of the A ring.7 Ester 27  was  refluxed  in  1:1  MeOH–CH2Cl2  containing  CSA  (5 equiv). When TLC monitoring showed complete consump- tion  of  27  (22  h),  the  solvents  were  removed  by  evapora- tion, and the crude material was further heated in refluxing benzene for two hours. Through this two-step protocol, two products were obtained. One was the desired lactone 28 in 47%  yield,  and  the  other  was  alcohol  29,35  lacking  the  B- ring,  in  32%  yield.  The  structures  of  28  and  29  were  as- signed by extensive NMR analyses.23 Thus, a viable synthet- ic approach to the AB-ring system had been developed, al- though there still remained room for improvement. In conclusion, we have described a promising approach to  the  asymmetric  synthesis  of  the  lactonamycins  devel- oped through a model study on the ABCD-ring system, in- cluding  (1)  construction  of  the  C-ring  by  an  asymmetric benzoin cyclization, (2) introduction of an angular hydroxy group through oxidation of an isoxazolium salt, and (3) the TFAA 2,6-lutidine CH2Cl2, –20 °C; . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C s t t e s u h c a s s a M strategic coherence of the seven-membered cyclic structure 9  as  a  precursor  to  the  AB-ring  system.  Further  work  to- ward a total synthesis is ongoing in our laboratory.
